<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-128-842  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 128 842.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Proceedings of the IEEE  Nov 1989 v77 n11 p1728(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Advances in weather technology for the aviation system.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCarthy, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Federal Aviation Administration's national airspace planfor air traffic modernization and the National Weather Service'stotal revision of its weather observational capability willcombine to improve the US aviation system considerably.andP;  The NextGeneration Radar (NEXRAD) network of Doppler weather radarsconnects 150 radars throughout the US, but microburst wind shearcannot be detected by NEXRAD alone because of its radar scanningand siting limitations.andP;  The Terminal Doppler Weather Radar (TDWR)provides wind shear protection at about 50 US airports.andP;  TheAutomated Weather Observing System (AWOS) will consist of about1,000 automated surface weather observing systems at small andmedium-sized airports throughout the US.andP;  AWOS will provide pilotswith minute-by-minute weather information.andP;  Several other weathermeasurement modernization programs are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MeteorologyAir Traffic ControlControl SystemsMeasurement TechniquesEnhancementsResearch and DevelopmentGovernment AgencyUnited States. Federal Aviation AdministrationUnited States. National Weather Service.andO;Feature:   illustrationmap.andO;Caption:   Tentative coverage locations for the NWS and FAA AWOS systems.andO;(map)Preliminary placement of 47 terminal Doppler weather radarsystems. (map)Locations of central US atmospheric wind profiler network. (map)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>